   "source": [
    "# Perceptron Classifier Demo\n",
    "This notebook walks through training a **single-layer perceptron** on the Iris dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "## What is a Perceptron?\n",
    "A perceptron is a linear classifier inspired by a biological neuron. It computes a weighted sum of inputs and applies a sign/threshold activation.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Learning Rule\n",
    "The perceptron learning rule updates weights when a sample is misclassified:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$ w := w + \eta (y - \hat{y}) x $$\n",
    "\n",
    "- $w$: weights, $x$: input features, $y$: true label, $\hat{y}$: predicted label, $\eta$: learning rate.\n",
    "- Updates only occur for mistakes, nudging the decision boundary to correct them.\n",
    "- Works only when classes are linearly separable; otherwise it may not converge.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Why Scale Features?\n",
    "Gradient-like updates are sensitive to feature magnitudes. Standardizing features to zero mean and unit variance helps the perceptron converge faster and keeps the decision boundary well-behaved."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "from app.data import load_iris_dataset\n",
    "from app.model import build_perceptron_pipeline\n",
    "from app.preprocess import train_test_split_scaled\n",
    "from app.evaluate import evaluate_predictions, confusion, full_classification_report\n",
    "from app.visualize import plot_confusion_matrix, plot_pca_scatter\n"
   ],
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Load and split\n",
    "X, y = load_iris_dataset()\n",
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, scaler = train_test_split_scaled(X, y)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Build and train\n",
    "model = build_perceptron_pipeline()\n",
    "model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Predict\n",
    "y_pred = model.predict(X_test)"
   ],
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "metrics = evaluate_predictions(y_test, y_pred)\n",
    "metrics\n"
   ],
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "print(full_classification_report(y_test, y_pred))\n",
    "conf_matrix = confusion(y_test, y_pred)\n",
    "plot_confusion_matrix(conf_matrix, class_labels=y.unique())\n",
    "\n",
    "scaled_features = scaler.transform(X)\n",
    "plot_pca_scatter(scaled_features, y)\n"
   ],
   "execution_count": null,
   "outputs": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Limitations and Next Steps\n",
    "- Perceptrons learn linear decision boundaries only. Non-linearly separable problems will not be solved well.\n",
    "- Try **kernel methods** or **multilayer perceptrons (MLPs)** for more complex patterns.\n",
    "- Experiment with other linear solvers such as `SGDClassifier`."
   ]
  }
